				<p><p>I'm not aware of any technical name for the alignment of the wheels except -- literally -- <strong>"steering"</strong>.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.rehab.research.va.gov/jour/99/36/1/brienza.htm" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><img src="https://i.stack.imgur.com/v0AtB.gif" alt="Pivot points"></a></p>

<p>Spot turns in theory are no different than any other turn.  You simply align the axis of each wheel with the radial lines coming from a single pivot point.  If that point is underneath the vehicle, you will be doing a spot turn (a.k.a. point turn, a.k.a. pivot turn).  If the point is not underneath the vehicle, you will be doing a regular arcing turn like you'd do in a car or bicycle or similar.<br>
<a href="http://www.hemmings.com/hcc/stories/2013/09/01/hmn_feature15.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><img src="https://i.stack.imgur.com/vaTlcm.png" alt="ackerman angles"></a></p>

<p>Even if not all the wheels have adjustable angles, you're still orienting all the wheels to the same point.</p>
</p><br>
